			<h1>1. Green buildings</h1>
 
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;With the effects of climate change being felt across the globe, green buildings have<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;become a necessity, to ensure a sustainable future.</p>
 
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Sustainability is no longer an option but the need of the hour, conserve the resources<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;to and protect the environment.</p>
  
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The increase in environmental awareness among people, has impacted real estate in India too.</p>
  
			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;In the last few years, green buildings in India have seen a dramatic increase.</p>

			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;A green building is one that is designed and built to reduce environmental impacts.</p>

			<p class="p5"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Green buildings are a trillion-dollar industry, worldwide.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-3">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Approach3.png">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>

			<h1> 2. Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design</h1>
 
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;“India had 899 LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design)-certified projects<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp; totalling more than 24.81 million gross sq metres of space in 2018.</p>

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Currently, we have close to 3,200 LEED participating projects totalling 1.45 billion gross sq ft</p>

			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;India is steadily working toward its target of 10 billion sq ft of green building footprint by 2022,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;on the back of several initiatives and programmes.</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;India has consistently ranked third (outside of the US) in the annual list of the top 10 countries<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and regions in the LEED list”</p>

			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Many government buildings in the country have chosen LEED certification.</p>

			<p class="p5"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;State governments in Maharashtra, Uttar Pradesh, Haryana, Punjab, Rajasthan, West Bengal<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and Andhra Pradesh, have started offering incentives for the rating system and government<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;agencies have been persuading property buyers to opt for sustainable buildings with<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;LEED certification</p>

			<p class="p6"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The GBCI considers five key parameters for LEED certification: saving energy, saving water,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;waste management, reducing carbon footprint and focusing on the health of the<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;building’s occupants.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-4">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Approach4.jpg">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>3. Environmental impact of Construction</h1>
			
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Climate change is happening. Global warming may cause sea levels to rise,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;resulting in the flooding of low-lying coastal areas in the future.</p>
			
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Buildings and their usage attribute around 40% to this. “Resources are limited and <br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;waste disposal has become a serious issue.</p>
			
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;We have to look at an alternative approach. Practising ‘sustainable architecture’ <br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;should be the norm.</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Conservation of our existing buildings should be our top priority.</p>

			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; The construction of new buildings has a great impact on the environment and<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;should be kept to the minimum.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-5">
			
			<img class="main-img" src="Approach5.jpg">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>4. Conserve Natural Resources</h1>

			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Green buildings consume less water, make optimal use of energy, conserve natural resources and<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;generate less waste, while providing healthier living spaces for its occupants,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;as compared to conventional buildings.</p> 

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;For residents, this translates into tangible benefits in the form of savings in water <br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and electricity bills, while intangible benefits include enhanced ventilation, adequate<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;daylight, superior air quality and an overall sense of harmony and well-being.</p>

			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The vision for green buildings is to have a zero-carbon footprint. There is a growing trend,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;today, to utilise unconventional alternatives for conserving natural resources</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Home buyers are increasingly becoming aware of the benefits of living in green homes <br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and are demanding the same.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-6">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Approach6.gif">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>5.Sustainable construction technologies in real estate</h1>
			
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;There are many ways, in which real estate can embrace sustainable construction technologies.</p>
			
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;At the construction stage, one can ensure that existing water bodies are preserved,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;to minimise ecological disturbance.</p>
			
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Opt for Gypsum plaster, as an alternate material to cement and sand plaster,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;as this requires 50% less water for mixing and no water for curing.</p>

 			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; A curing compound can be used instead of water, to reduce water consumption<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;in projects.</p>

 			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Water-efficient fixtures can minimise wastage and recycled water can be used for landscaping.</p>

 			<p class="p5"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; In addition to bricks, fly ash can be used in the construction of roads and <br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;flooring of car parking areas. The use of fly ash reduces dependencies on cement,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;which is linked to CO2 emissions. Fly ash also enhances thermal efficiency, keeping interiors cool<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;in summer and warm in winter.</p>

 			<p class="p6"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Constructions can also incorporate features that minimise energy consumption.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;Natural ventilation can often be a problem in Indian cities with high pollution levels.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;To counter this, one can use shaded and comfortable outdoor landscape and introduce indoor plants</p>

 			<p class="p7"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Alternative cooling strategies, like natural ventilation enhanced by ceiling fans<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and desert coolers, can provide thermal comfort for a large part of the year<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and reduce the need for energy-guzzling air-conditioners.</p>

 			<p class="p8"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Indoor plants or green walls can also minimise the harmful effects of poor outdoor air quality.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;For water conservation, dual piping systems with a centralised sewage treatment plant, can help utilise grey water for secondary requirements,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;like flushing, irrigation, etc. Rainwater harvesting for large developments, can cater to freshwater demand.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;Renewable energy for common areas and solar heaters, can help in energy efficiency</p>

 			<p class="p9"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Although the construction industry and consumers are moving towards sustainable practices, there is a shortfall of sustainable design experts and technically skilled manpower,<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;to execute these objectives, Bansal laments. “The industry needs to evolve holistically and this should include education and training infrastructure.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;Accelerating the adoption of green buildings, will require advanced training and education infrastructure, enhanced financial support, as well as better incentive schemes.</p>

